0. Reading in the data, creating AnnData object¶

We will only need the normalised, scaled and centered expression values, the cluster IDs, and the tSNE coordinates. We compile those into an AnnData object, for further use with ScanPy.

In [3]:

import anndata as ad
import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
In [4]:

cluster_ids = pd.read_csv("./data/clusters_42_34_and_oddcells_reassigned.txt", header=None, sep=" ", index_col=0)

2. Calculate PAGA based on the PCA¶

Unfortunately, we did not keep track of the random seed, so to ensure reproducibility of the figures in the paper, we will provide the principal components we used.

In [10]:
pca = np.loadtxt("./data/210301_sl_PCs.txt")
adata.obsm["X_pca"] = pca
In [11]:
sc.pp.neighbors(adata, n_neighbors=10, n_pcs=100)
sc.tl.paga(adata, groups="annot")

Let's have a look at the distribution of PAGA connectivity values; this will guide us in choosing appropriate thresholds.

In [12]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
In [13]:
tmp = adata.uns["paga"]["connectivities"].toarray()
paga = tmp[np.triu_indices(tmp.shape[0])]

fig, ax = plt.subplots()
ax.hist(paga, bins=50);

Clearly bimodal distribution, with a lot of 0s and quite some 1s. This suggests that a cutoff between 0.5-0.9 might be appropriate to reveal the base structure of the data. Our analysis suggested that 0.7 was a good cutoff.

3. Plotting¶

We will plot the tSNE using the colors of the main paper, the PAGA plot with the same structure as the tSNE, a PAGA plot colored by #unique_marker_genes per cluster, and a plot of gene expression over pseudotime, counting each cluster's distance from the archaeocyte cluster. We will keep referring to the tSNE embedding and the "annot" slot that we created above:

In [14]:
cluster = "annot"
embedding = "X_tsne"

3.1 tSNE only, with small dots and alpha = 0.2¶

In [15]:
cluster_cols = np.repeat("#FFFFFF", adata.shape[0])

ax.axis('off');

3.2 PAGA graph¶

This is the default PAGA plot. There are multiple options to explore that could improve its aesthetics, but we want to put the cluster centers at the median positions of the cells of the tSNE cluster, so we need a custom solution. We will set the root to cluster 0, the bigger archaeocyte cluster:

In [16]:
sc.pl.paga(adata, threshold=0.7, layout="fr", root=0)

3.3 Custom PAGA graph with cluster IDs¶

To improve the readability of our custom plot:

  • we will color all PAGA connections with a weight below 1.00 gray.
  • we will scale line width linearly with the PAGA weight values. Since we place the PAGA cutoff at 0.7, the difference in line width between strong and weaker connections is not going to be so clear. We will rescale every value to exaggerate that, using 0.6 as the floor.
In [17]:
threshold = 0.7
gray_threshold = 0.99
lwd_floor = 0.6
centers = adata.uns["paga"]["pos"]
connectivities = np.array(adata.uns["paga"]["connectivities"].todense())

In [19]:
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(6, 6))
ax.axis('off')
counts = np.zeros(adata.obs[cluster].cat.categories.shape)
for i, c in enumerate(adata.obs["annot"].cat.categories):
    cluster_points = adata.obsm[embedding][adata.obs[cluster] == c]
    centers[i] = np.median(cluster_points, axis=0)
    counts[i] = np.sum(adata.obs[cluster] == adata.obs[cluster].cat.categories[i])
for i, row in enumerate(connectivities):
    for j, _col in enumerate(row):
        if connectivities[i, j] > threshold:
            if threshold > 0:
                conn = (connectivities[i, j] - lwd_floor) / (1 - lwd_floor)
            else:
                conn = connectivities[i, j]
            if connectivities[i, j] > gray_threshold:
                con_col = "black"
            else:
                con_col = "gray"
            ax.plot(
                [centers[i, 0], centers[j, 0]],
                [centers[i, 1], centers[j, 1]],
                linewidth= (conn),
                c=con_col,
                zorder=0,
            )
ax.scatter(centers[:, 0], centers[:, 1], color=adata.uns["annot_colors"], s=25 * np.log(counts), zorder=1, edgecolors="black", marker="o");

3.4 Number of unique marker genes¶

To add the number of unique marker genes we will just do a maplotlib plot and not go back to scanpy. Just use the c= attribute of scatter plot, sicne that gives us easier colorbars

In [20]:
no_marker_genes = pd.read_csv("/Users/papadopoulos/Documents/data/spongilla/unique_marker_gene_table.tsv", sep="\t")

# this list only has the clusters with #unique marker genes > 0; so we will have to create an empty
# vector of size 42 (initial number of clusters) and then select everything except positions 34, 42

tmp = np.zeros(42)
tmp[no_marker_genes.cluster_number-1] = no_marker_genes.unique_genes

keep = ~np.isin(np.arange(42), [33, 41])
unique_marker_genes_annot = tmp[keep]

We will plot the log(#genes) so that very rich clusters (like the archaeocytes) don't overwhelm our color bar. For the same reason we will cap log(#genes) at 4 to make it easier to see which nodes have lots of unique marker genes (and ignore the cells that have enormous amounts of UMGs):

In [21]:
unique_capped = np.log(unique_marker_genes_annot + 1)
unique_capped[unique_capped > 4] = 4

No need to re-set thresholds or re-calculate cluster centers/point sizes, as we did that already

4. Plot gene expression along tree¶

To do that we will calculate diffusion maps and diffusion pseudotime, starting from the archaeocyte cluster. To avoid archaeocytes (which are severely overrepresented in the data) dominating the gene expression plots, we will subsample the archaeocyte clusters randomly.

First, let's fix the gene names: We will extract the Trinity ID of each gene from the index and save the index as "long_name". We will then set the gene index to the Trinity ID, since this will make plotting easier down the line.

In [23]:
adata.var["trinity"] = adata.var.index.str.split(" ").str[0]
adata.var["long_names"] = adata.var.index
adata.var_names = adata.var.trinity

Now we will set one cell in the archaeocyte 0 cluster as the root, then calculate the diffusion map. The data is already normalised, log-transformed, scaled, and centered.

In [24]:
adata.uns['iroot'] = np.flatnonzero(adata.obs['annot']  == 'archaeo 0')[0]

sc.tl.diffmap(adata)
sc.pp.neighbors(adata, n_neighbors=10, use_rep='X_diffmap')
sc.tl.dpt(adata)

adata.obs['distance'] = adata.obs['dpt_pseudotime']
In [25]:
sc.pl.tsne(adata, color="dpt_pseudotime")
